\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\nowidctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs24 So who or what did Americans think black people were?  In 1915, David Wark Griffith\rquote s blockbuster movie \'93Birth of a Nation\'94
 hit the public like a thunderbolt, and President Woodrow Wilson, who had a screening of it in the White House (it was the first movie to be shown in the White House) described it as \'93history written in lightning.\'94
  The White House did not disclose that Rev. Thomas Dixon, who was the author of }{\i\f0\fs24 The Clansman}{\f0\fs24 , a 1905 novel that the movie was based on, happened to be Woodrow Wilson\rquote s grad school chum.  But mos
t people, black people, anyway, understood where the Wilson administration\rquote s racial ideas came from.  Not only did \'93The Birth of a Nation\'94 make lots and lots of money at the box office, it also revitalized the revived Atlanta\_
based Ku Klux Klan.  In fact, at the movie\rquote s premiere in Atlanta, while people stood on line, Klansmen rode down the street on horseback handing out membership applications to the moviegoers.
\par But that was 1915.  
\par 1917 proved that poetry could be hazardous to your health, your bank acco
