n
age Act passed in 1917, followed by the Sedition Act passed in 1918, prepared the United States to enter as a combatant in World War I.  Albert Burleson, the Postmaster General, was able to use the Espionage Act and the Sedition Act to deny mailing privil
eges to any publication that published material critical of the government's war effort.  That act was invoked in 1917 to prevent distribution of the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24 
