\par }\pard \ql \fi709\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\nowidctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs24 Now, that poem was supposed to appear in the August 1917 issue of the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24 
.  Postmaster General Burleson seized the issue and refused to have it mailed.  Eastman and company were indicted and tried for obstructing recruitment.  The judge dismissed charges against Josephine Bell when he discovered that she really couldn\rquote 
t be much of a conspirator, inasmuch as like most of the rest of us, I suppose she had simply sent in her poem with a stamped, self\_addressed envelope, and Max Eastman and the rest decided to print it.  
\par But the readers of the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24  knew Emma Goldman as a trained nurse who campaigned vigorously for birth control.  In April 1916, Goldman
 was arrested for giving a birth control lecture.  She decided, like Marcus Garvey and other people that don\rquote t have too much sense, to defend herself.  She was convicted, of course, and sentenced to 15 days in jail.  But the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{
\f0\fs24 , in its June 1916 issue, published her courtroom speech.  Partly it said, \'93Your Honor, if giving one\rquote 
s life for the purpose of awakening race consciousness in the masses, a consciousness that will impel them to bring quality and not quantity into society, if that be a crime, I\rquote m glad to be such a criminal.\'94  
\par \'93After all,\'94 she went on, \'93the question of birth control is largely a working man\rquote s question.  Above all, a working woman\rquote s question.  She it is who risks her health, her youth, her very life, in giving out of herself the uni
ts of the race.  She it is who ought to have the means and the knowledge to say how many children she shall give, and to what purpose she shall give them, and under what conditions she shall bring forth life.\'94 
\par I suppose that that\rquote s the Emma Goldman that Josephine Bell was thinking of when she wrote the poem.  
\par Alexander Berkman is a somewhat different story.  He was an anarchist who attempted to assassinate Carnegie Steel executive Henry Clay Frick during the Homestead Strike.  He spent fourteen years in p
rison, but he went on giving his political speeches once he got out.  The }{\i\f0\fs24 cause c\'e9l\'e8bre }{\f0\fs24 
of 1917 is that both Goldman and Berkman were arrested for obstructing the draft.  And that has something to do with  the Post Office citing Josephine Bell\rquote s poem. 
