\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\nowidctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs24 Max Eastman and his associates had a lot of financial backing.  And they went through two trials and won.  But, of course, the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24 
 magazine went defunct in the interim, and he replaced it with a magazine called }{\i\f0\fs24 Liberator}{\f0\fs24 .  
\par Besides birth control and the draft, race was a particularly sensitive issue to the government, partly because these years\emdash before the Jazz Age and the Harlem Renaissance and America\rquote s involvement in World War I\emdash 
provided a great deal of material for those people who wanted to point out that democracy, in some parts of this country anyway, was quite as unsafe as it was anyplace else in the world.  In September 1916, the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24 
 ran an eyewitness report on conditions in Waco, Texas, the day after a 17\_year\_
old black youth named Jesse Washington was dragged out of the courtroom where he was being tried, and roasted over a bonfire in the courthouse square.  Photographs taken from the vantage point of City Hall
 were later sold as postcards, souvenirs of that incident.  The NAACP journal, the }{\i\f0\fs24 Crisis}{\f0\fs24 , devoted a whole issue\emdash I believe it was in September 1916\emdash to that Waco atrocity. 
\par Fenton Johnson\rquote s Chicago magazine the }{\i\f0\fs24 Champion}{\f0\fs24  pointedly compared Waco to the casual
ties incurred by a black cavalry unit on duty in Mexico.  They were on a mission to arrest Pancho Villa, but they blundered into the Mexican Civil War and were taken prisoners, resulting in President Wilson calling up National Guardsmen and massing fifty 
thousand in Texas troops at the border\endash threatening war with Mexico.  
\par The African\_American press, like the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24 , was also subject to the intimidation of government readers, so to speak; and, unlike the }{\i\f0\fs24 Masses}{\f0\fs24  and other wealthy liberals, did not have the r
esources to fight against it.  During 1918, the Justice Department under Attorney General A. Mitchell Palmer conducted extensive research and surveillance with a newly\_established task force.  And that group, headed by a young man named J. Edgar Hoover
\emdash on his first job\emdash explored and researched what Hoover called \'93radicalism and sedition among Negroes as reflected in their publications.\'94
  They published a wonderful report in the documents of the 66th Congress, issued by the Government Printing Office, which essentially is quite an interesting anthology of African\_American writing in 1915, 1916, 1917, 1918, and 1919.  
\par Newspaper and magazine editors also might get a visit from Maj. Walter Loving, who was a black Army officer.  He earned his commission in the Sp
anish-American War.  There were very few black officers in the United States Army then; none in the United States Navy.  But Walter Loving was attached to the Military Intelligence Branch  (MIB) and worked in plainclothes, attending political and intellec
tual meetings in Harlem, Chicago and elsewhere.  Of course everyone knew who he was.  When he showed up to have an appointment with Robert Abbott at the }{\i\f0\fs24 Chicago Defender, }{\f0\fs24 
Mr. Abbott knew that the message was that some of his editorials had annoyed someone in Washington, D.C. 
\par Here in Houston, in September 1917, what is now Memorial Park was called Camp Logan.  And the same 9}{\f0\fs24\super th}{\f0\fs24  and 10}{\f0\fs24\super th}{\f0\fs24  Cavalry, and the 25th Infantry\emdash the \'93Buffalo soldiers\'94\emdash 
that had gotten in the scrape in Mexico in 1916, were stationed here as security guards for the building of Camp Logan. The facility was intended to be a training base for those soldiers going to Europe\emdash \'93over there\'94
 where the Yanks were coming.  After a month or so of insults and racist abuse from the Houston Police Department and the public, an incident took place on San Felipe Street.  The soldiers were outraged and marched on the town from their base.  That
\rquote s described as the Houston Riot.  The upshot is several people were killed.  Most were black soldiers, also white policemen and citizens who armed themselves to attack the soldiers or perhaps to defend them.  
\par Thirteen of the soldiers were court\_martialed and hanged.  Forty\_one were court\_martialed and given life imprisonment.  All of these trials went on within a bewild
eringly short period of time, much before the press knew anything about the incident.  When Archibald Grimk\'e9, who was a well\_known lawyer in Washington, D.C., wrote a poem called \'93Her Thirteen Black Soldiers,\'94 it was rejected by the }{
\i\f0\fs24 Atlantic Monthly}{\f0\fs24 .  It went from there to the }{\i\f0\fs24 Crisis}{\f0\fs24 , which was edited by W.E.B. Du Bois, and according to Jervis Anderson in his biography of A. Philip Randolph, Du Bois admitted to Archibald Grimk\'e9 that
\emdash even though Grimk\'e9 was head of the Washington D.C. NAACP chapter\emdash because of Justice Department scrutiny and the fact that the Justice Department had found some of Du Bois\rquote s }{\i\f0\fs24 Crisis }{\f0\fs24 
editorials disloyal, he dared not print this poem. A. Philip Randolph\rquote s }{\i\f0\fs24 Messenger}{\f0\fs24  did eventually print the poem \'93Her Thirteen Black Soldiers,\'94 along with an editorial note pointing out that both  the }{\i\f0\fs24 
Atlantic Monthly}{\f0\fs24  and the }{\i\f0\fs24 Crisis}{\f0\fs24  had not dared to print the poem. 
\par That editorial note was typical of Randolph\rquote s style at the time.  J. Edgar Hoover\rquote s investigative report to Congress described the }{\i\f0\fs24 Messenger}{\f0\fs24  magazine, a socialist journal, as the \'93
most dangerous of the Negro publications\'94\emdash a quotation which Randolph and his co\_editor Chandler Owen promptly used as an advertising blurb.  But in 1919 the }{\i\f0\fs24 Messenger}{\f0\fs24  still had the national resources of the Socialist 
Party to support it; when that went away in a few years, they no longer used that line as an advertising blurb
